The paper deals with the problem of reducing the worst-case quadratic complexity of edge-discovery applications over graph-based data models, which is a common problem in several areas of computer science, including database systems (cs.DB), artificial intelligence (cs.AI), machine learning (cs.LG), information retrieval (cs.IR), and social networks (cs.SI). The paper specifically focuses on the problem of entity resolution and type alignment between heterogeneous RDF graphs, which is a subfield of database systems and artificial intelligence. Therefore, cs.DB and cs.AI are the most likely sub-categories. However, the paper also presents a graph-theoretic formalism for DNF schemes and investigates their learnability in an optimization framework, which are topics that are relevant to machine learning (cs.LG) and information retrieval (cs.IR). Finally, the paper mentions link prediction in networks represented as attributed graphs, which is a topic that falls under the sub-category of social networks (cs.SI).
